'''Roger Felix Turner''' (March 3, 1901 &ndash; October 29, 1993) was an [[United States|American]] [[figure skater]].
He was born in [[Milton, Massachusetts]] and died in [[Walpole, Massachusetts]].
Turner was the seven time (1928â1934) [[United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S. National Champion]] and two time (1930â1931) [[World Figure Skating Championships|World silver medalist]]. He is tied with [[Dick Button]] for having the most consecutive wins at the U.S. Championships (men's singles). Turner was inducted into the United States Figure Skating Hall of Fame in 1994. He was a member of the [[Skating Club of Boston]].
At the [[1928 Winter Olympics]] he finished tenth in the [[Figure skating at the 1928 Winter Olympics - Men's singles|singles competition]]. Four years later at the [[1932 Winter Olympics|Lake Placid Games]] he finished sixth in the [[Figure skating at the 1928 Winter Olympics - Men's singles|singles event]].
